Q.What is BiProducer?

Ans: Firstly there is no Producer, there is Supplier.
Secondly there is no BiSupplier of any sort. Let's see the reason:

4️⃣ Producer Side (Supplier) 🏭

Java doesn’t call it “Producer” — it’s called Supplier.

5️⃣ Supplier (Produces ONE thing)

🧠 Meaning

Takes nothing, returns something

Syntax:
Supplier<T>

Method:
T get();

Example:

Supplier<Double> random =
        () -> Math.random();

System.out.println(random.get());

6️⃣ Is There a BiSupplier? ❌

❌ NO BiSupplier in Java

Why?

Supplier already produces without input
Two outputs don’t make sense as a single return

If needed → wrap in object/record.

7️⃣ Big Picture Table 🧠

Interface	                    Input	             Output	                      Example Use

Consumer	                      1	                  none	                      print, save
BiConsumer	                      2	                  none	                      map.forEach
Supplier	                      0	                  1	                          lazy creation

8️⃣ Interview One-Liners ⭐

(i) Consumer:
“Consumes an input and performs an action without returning a result.”

(ii) BiConsumer:
“Consumes two inputs and performs an action without returning a result.”

(iii) Supplier:
“Supplies or produces a value without taking any input.”

9️⃣ Easy Memory Trick 🧠

Consumer  → eats data 🍽️
Supplier  → gives data 🎁
Function  → transforms data 🔄
Predicate → checks data ❓

